    <text id="B0084T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Jackson writes McDonnell about the Alexander-McCutchen case, noting the the
                    administrator of the McCutchen estate requires legal proof before he will settle
                    the claim.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient"><abbr expan="Captain">Capt.</abbr> John A.
                            McDonnell<lb/><abbr expan="Sub Assistant Commissioner">Sub Asst Com<hi
                                rend="super">r</hi></abbr><lb/>Winchester</name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-12-17"><abbr expan="December">Dec</abbr> 17, 1867</date>
                        <name type="place">Staunton, Va</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Captain</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>I respectfully refer to a communication from <abbr expan="Brevet">Brev</abbr>
                    <abbr expan="Lieutenant Colonel">Lt. Col.</abbr> James Johnson <abbr
                        expan="Sub Assistant Commissioner">S.A.C.</abbr> 6th <abbr expan="District"
                        >Dist.</abbr>
                    <abbr expan="Virginia">Va.</abbr> dated May 1/67 (returned to your Head Quarters
                    May 12/67 with an endorsement thereon made by me. May 12/67) asking aid to
                    collect a claim of $130 said to be due to the children of Henry Alexander (<abbr
                        expan="colored">col'd</abbr>) by James McPhetus McCutchen, deceased, lately
                    of Augusta <abbr expan="County">Co.</abbr> Claimant in behalf of the children of
                    Benjamin Moten (<abbr expan="colored">col'd</abbr>)</p>

                <p>The heirs dispute the claim and the Administrator notifies me that unless legal
                    proof is presented he cannot pay the amount or any portion thereof. As the
                    estate is solvent and must soon be settled, I ask Henry Alexander's children
                        <unclear>furnish</unclear> me at once with proper legal proof of the
                    solidity of their claim.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Very Respectfully <lb/>Yr. Obt. Servt</salute>
                    <signed>Thos. P. Jackson, Agent</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
